WEBVTT

00:06.767 --> 00:09.567
We've got facial drooping
and paralysis.

00:09.567 --> 00:11.167
My bet is he's had a stroke.

00:11.167 --> 00:13.500
Your emergency patient,
it seems, will survive,

00:13.500 --> 00:15.100
but won't be the man he was.

00:15.100 --> 00:17.667
I've been contacted
by the Israeli Embassy.

00:17.667 --> 00:20.733
If I'm agreeable,
they'll ask Menzies to add me

00:20.733 --> 00:23.033
to our diplomatic staff
in Israel.

00:23.033 --> 00:25.067
Evens we stay.

00:25.867 --> 00:27.100
Odds we go.

00:27.100 --> 00:29.133
ANNA: He was wondering
if I had any ideas

00:29.133 --> 00:30.667
for radio serials.

00:30.667 --> 00:33.167
I was thinking "Tender Vines."

00:33.167 --> 00:34.833
I forgot to mention
there may be an extra.

00:34.833 --> 00:36.167
-Oh, yes?
-He didn't commit.

00:36.167 --> 00:38.233
-Who are you expecting?
-Just Harry Polson.

00:39.033 --> 00:40.700
Adorable Harry.

00:40.700 --> 00:42.200
ZELDA:
You're not stuck on him?

00:42.200 --> 00:45.400
I think Douglas would approve
of a philanthropic endeavor.

00:46.000 --> 00:48.767
The obvious thought
is the refuge.

00:48.767 --> 00:50.067
Something of my own, I think.

00:50.067 --> 00:53.400
Something for women,
as Douglas helped men.

00:53.400 --> 00:55.433
JACK: Let's see what response
this gets.

00:55.433 --> 00:57.367
Blokes.
Talkin'.

00:57.367 --> 00:59.000
Well, stranger things
have happened.

01:00.333 --> 01:01.400
FRASER:
Next time.

01:02.467 --> 01:04.700
-If there is one.
-I'm in it for the long haul.

01:04.700 --> 01:08.367
Caro and me...
we're mucking along.

01:08.367 --> 01:10.067
How is she with that?

01:10.067 --> 01:12.200
Okay one day,
frustrated the next.

01:12.733 --> 01:15.667
[ Screams ]

01:15.667 --> 01:18.367
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

01:20.000 --> 01:26.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:37.967 --> 01:40.133
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

01:40.133 --> 01:41.767
DAVID:
Mummy's coming with Leah!

01:41.767 --> 01:44.733
She's here!
She's here!

01:44.733 --> 01:46.267
Leah!
Shalom!

01:46.267 --> 01:47.400
LEAH:
[ Laughs ]

01:47.400 --> 01:49.433
Shalom! Shalom!

01:49.433 --> 01:52.200
Oh!
Kisses from the kibbutz?

01:52.200 --> 01:54.067
-No kisses.
-[ Laughs ] I know, I know.

01:54.067 --> 01:56.533
-How is everyone there?
-They all send their love.

01:56.533 --> 01:58.200
And the clinic on the kibbutz?

01:58.200 --> 01:59.767
Oh, they miss Sarah.

01:59.767 --> 02:02.067
Guess what I've got!
A spaceship!

02:02.067 --> 02:03.600
A spaceship?!

02:03.600 --> 02:05.400
We can go to the moon!
Come on!

02:05.400 --> 02:07.867
Now, Leah's not here
to look after you, remember.

02:07.867 --> 02:09.267
But I need her to.

02:09.267 --> 02:10.967
She's got a different job now.

02:10.967 --> 02:13.400
She's gonna become a nurse,
like Mummy.

02:13.400 --> 02:15.867
And I've got you a surprise!
Come on!

02:15.867 --> 02:17.433
Uh, Uncle Isaac still well?

02:17.433 --> 02:19.967
Uh, yeah. He's very busy.
He's got two assistants now.

02:19.967 --> 02:21.167
I'm not surprised.

02:21.167 --> 02:23.633
And he wants to know
when you're coming back.

02:23.633 --> 02:25.933
Well, that depends.

02:25.933 --> 02:27.067
Come on, Leah!

02:27.067 --> 02:29.067
I give up.
[ Laughs ]

02:29.067 --> 02:30.700
All right.
Come on.

02:31.233 --> 02:33.267
Depends on what?

02:33.867 --> 02:35.167
Oh, no.

02:35.167 --> 02:37.067
-Oh. David.
-Uh, David!

02:37.067 --> 02:38.467
-David!
-Stop, please!

02:40.233 --> 02:43.600
* I got a fine-lookin' woman
dancing next to me *

02:43.600 --> 02:44.700
Your boyfriend.

02:45.233 --> 02:47.433
* She's a good-lookin' girl *

02:47.433 --> 02:48.667
* That's plain to see *

02:48.667 --> 02:51.233
David's excited
to know a rock-and-roll star.

02:51.233 --> 02:52.800
I'm -- I'm sorry.

02:52.800 --> 02:55.967
Um, it's what he always wanted,
Larry.

02:55.967 --> 02:57.967
It's just...

02:57.967 --> 02:59.633
It's a surprise.

02:59.633 --> 03:01.800
* Gonna take her home tonight *

03:01.800 --> 03:03.400
Too much grown-up talk?

03:03.400 --> 03:04.500
Yes.

03:04.500 --> 03:07.067
Come on, Mr. Groovy.

03:07.067 --> 03:08.133
Let's...

03:08.133 --> 03:10.467
-[ Volume increases ]
-...rock!

03:12.333 --> 03:14.500
Come on, Mrs. Groovy.

03:14.500 --> 03:17.367
Let's rock!
[ Laughs ]

03:17.367 --> 03:21.800
* Well, she looks just like
a high-class fashion show *

03:21.800 --> 03:22.967
[ Birds chirping ]

03:22.967 --> 03:25.500
So Leah will be joining you
as a nurse's aide

03:25.500 --> 03:28.067
until the next training intake
in the city.

03:28.067 --> 03:30.267
I'll be staying
with your Mrs. Collins.

03:30.267 --> 03:32.367
We can have some fun.

03:33.100 --> 03:35.933
Oh, uh, Dr. Duncan,

03:35.933 --> 03:38.567
I brought you and Mrs. Duncan
a little something.

03:43.367 --> 03:45.733
[ Door closes ]

03:45.733 --> 03:47.833
[ Knock, door opens ]

03:49.867 --> 03:51.533
SARAH:
I'm so sorry.

03:52.333 --> 03:54.333
In all the excitement
picking Leah up from the ship,

03:54.333 --> 03:56.167
-I didn't think --
-Why would you?

03:56.167 --> 03:57.867
We're old news.

03:58.633 --> 04:00.367
Should we, um...

04:00.367 --> 04:02.867
How about a walk
after you finish work?

04:02.867 --> 04:04.167
-Something.
-No, I'm good.

04:04.167 --> 04:05.467
Thanks.

04:05.467 --> 04:08.533
You can't keep avoiding Ash Park
forever.

04:08.533 --> 04:09.900
Come up for dinner.

04:09.900 --> 04:11.300
Anytime.
Just turn up.

04:11.300 --> 04:12.633
No.
I'm good.

04:16.132 --> 04:18.300
I know you don't want advice,
but --

04:18.300 --> 04:19.300
I would agree.

04:19.300 --> 04:21.600
-It's not...
-Leave it.

04:21.600 --> 04:24.100
It's not healthy
to shut people out.

04:24.833 --> 04:26.300
Anna rang the other night --

04:26.300 --> 04:27.600
Look.
If -- If you'll excuse me.

04:27.600 --> 04:29.433
She said you hung up on her.

04:29.433 --> 04:30.767
[ Sighs ]

04:30.767 --> 04:32.467
You know what?

04:33.233 --> 04:34.567
I'm the bad guy.

04:34.567 --> 04:37.233
Just -- Just all take Carolyn's
side and get on with it.

04:37.233 --> 04:38.633
No one's doing that.

04:38.633 --> 04:40.333
We're concerned.

04:40.900 --> 04:42.300
Are you talking to anyone?

04:42.300 --> 04:44.067
You at the moment.

04:45.500 --> 04:47.067
Well, you're not
going to like this,

04:47.067 --> 04:48.267
but if there's a man
in your group --

04:48.267 --> 04:50.900
Do not keep badgering me.

04:50.900 --> 04:52.067
I have work to do.

04:54.867 --> 04:57.100
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

04:57.100 --> 05:00.633
I-I haven't been badgering you,
Jack.

05:01.200 --> 05:03.833
I'm watching your back.
It's what friends d--

05:03.833 --> 05:06.967
You ever notice how you always
have to have the last word?

05:13.133 --> 05:15.800
[ Music continues ]

05:24.333 --> 05:26.833
[ Dramatic music plays ]

05:26.833 --> 05:29.067
[ Birds chirping ]

05:29.067 --> 05:31.600
MAN ON RADIO: And now
for today's emotional episode

05:31.600 --> 05:34.167
of "Tender Vines."

05:34.767 --> 05:37.767
"Tender Vines" -- the story
of a young country woman

05:37.767 --> 05:40.267
torn between two worlds.

05:40.833 --> 05:42.300
CHARLOTTE:
This time of year,

05:42.300 --> 05:44.567
Italian mamas were keeping
their eyes glued

05:44.567 --> 05:47.067
to their tomato crops.

05:47.067 --> 05:48.667
MRS. ANGELO:
[ Italian accent ] Charlotte.

05:48.667 --> 05:49.967
CHARLOTTE:
Yes, Mrs. Angelo?

05:49.967 --> 05:52.167
MRS. ANGELO:
You come to our festa, darling?

05:52.167 --> 05:54.200
Everyone make passata.

05:54.200 --> 05:55.867
You bring your papa, yes?

05:55.867 --> 05:59.833
CHARLOTTE: I'm sorry, signora.
He won't be able to come.

05:59.833 --> 06:01.600
It was because he was angry.

06:01.600 --> 06:03.200
It was one thing
to make friends

06:03.200 --> 06:04.733
with the poor Italian farmers.

06:04.733 --> 06:08.067
It was another to fall in love
with their sons.

06:08.067 --> 06:10.400
It's all a bit puzzling.

06:10.400 --> 06:13.133
She left him, after all.

06:13.133 --> 06:15.967
She had hoped to do it
without hurting him.

06:15.967 --> 06:19.633
If she's so miserable,
perhaps she should go back.

06:19.633 --> 06:21.767
Without his changing
significantly,

06:21.767 --> 06:23.500
-what would be the point?
-Mm.

06:23.500 --> 06:26.067
She'd be on exactly
the same roundabout as before.

06:26.067 --> 06:27.067
[ Sighs ]

06:27.067 --> 06:30.067
Work plasters over pain,
I suppose.

06:30.067 --> 06:32.167
Until it doesn't.

06:32.167 --> 06:34.600
FATHER: Charlotte, you and Primo
are just friends, aren't you?

06:34.600 --> 06:35.933
CHARLOTTE:
Not really, Father.

06:35.933 --> 06:37.433
AUNT:
They're in love.

06:37.433 --> 06:39.400
You're the last one to see it.

06:39.400 --> 06:41.300
FATHER: You must never,
ever see him again.

06:41.300 --> 06:44.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

06:44.067 --> 06:46.067
[ Metal clattering ]

06:47.067 --> 06:47.967
Jack!

06:48.067 --> 06:48.933
Jack!

06:49.067 --> 06:50.867
Jack, I can explain!
Jack!

06:50.867 --> 06:52.767
-Really? Well, so can I.
-Please --

06:52.767 --> 06:54.500
You've had one foot out the door
ever since we met!

06:54.500 --> 06:56.700
-Please!
-That's it!

06:56.700 --> 06:59.067
CHARLOTTE: What if I live with
the Angelos for six months?

06:59.067 --> 07:00.633
I'll prove
it's the life I want.

07:00.633 --> 07:02.633
FATHER: Charlotte, you are not
thinking straight.

07:02.633 --> 07:04.700
CHARLOTTE:
Primo is the love of my life.

07:04.700 --> 07:06.900
[ Dramatic music plays,
radio turns off ]

07:11.433 --> 07:13.767
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

07:13.767 --> 07:15.767
[ Birds squawking ]

07:15.767 --> 07:18.200
[ Hammer tapping,
handsaw scraping ]

07:22.267 --> 07:25.067
How wonderful to see you!

07:25.067 --> 07:27.500
Oh!
How was the flight?

07:27.500 --> 07:30.600
Georgie met the pilot.

07:30.600 --> 07:32.567
ELIZABETH:
Did you? Oh!

07:34.800 --> 07:37.800
You really meant
a construction site.

07:38.333 --> 07:39.767
I filled her in.

07:39.767 --> 07:42.267
Not that we could actually have
a conversation in the car.

07:42.267 --> 07:44.667
A certain radio serial
was on the air.

07:44.667 --> 07:46.267
Yes.
The entire city stops.

07:46.267 --> 07:48.600
Grandmother gets very cross
if people don't listen.

07:48.600 --> 07:50.733
ELIZABETH:
[ Chuckles ]

07:51.267 --> 07:54.300
Oh, this baby just loves
the sound of carpentry.

07:54.300 --> 07:56.700
-A boy, do you think?
-Hm.

07:56.700 --> 07:59.667
We'll all be staying down here
while they're working upstairs.

07:59.667 --> 08:01.933
I'll organize some refreshments?

08:01.933 --> 08:04.567
What about a hot chocolate
for you before you have a sleep?

08:04.567 --> 08:06.300
Yes, please.

08:06.300 --> 08:09.633
I bought you a present with
my own money -- French money.

08:09.633 --> 08:10.700
Did you?

08:10.700 --> 08:12.667
Oh, you're so grown up.

08:12.667 --> 08:14.700
[ Chuckles ]

08:15.533 --> 08:17.100
She's in her element.

08:17.100 --> 08:20.333
Well, she would be if you
and that architect got together.

08:20.333 --> 08:22.367
She's been matching you two up
in her mind for weeks.

08:22.367 --> 08:23.367
Anna --

08:23.367 --> 08:24.867
Did you see the look
he gave you?

08:24.867 --> 08:26.233
I did.

08:26.767 --> 08:29.367
I may not be on the market.

08:29.900 --> 08:31.200
Excuse me?

08:32.299 --> 08:34.067
What does that mean?

08:34.067 --> 08:35.700
Olivia.

08:38.067 --> 08:40.232
In my own time.

08:40.232 --> 08:43.567
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

08:43.567 --> 08:46.600
So the idea came from Jack,
really.

08:46.600 --> 08:49.833
It's in some ways an extension
of the women's clinic

08:49.833 --> 08:52.567
and Douglas' refuge.

08:52.567 --> 08:57.400
A place for single women,
like Anna and Carolyn,

08:57.400 --> 08:59.633
women who might need somewhere
to give birth.

08:59.633 --> 09:02.067
Nonjudgmental.
Secular.

09:02.067 --> 09:03.767
Where will you live
when it's done?

09:03.767 --> 09:05.533
Prudence and I have decided
that her place

09:05.533 --> 09:07.167
is more than big enough
for both of us.

09:07.167 --> 09:08.800
Sorority girls.

09:09.567 --> 09:12.767
As soon as she who shall not
be named is on her merry way.

09:12.767 --> 09:14.933
Grandmother, that's unfair.

09:14.933 --> 09:16.200
Delia.

09:16.200 --> 09:18.467
And you know nothing more
has happened between them.

09:18.467 --> 09:21.233
Perhaps, but Carolyn
is being stubborn.

09:21.233 --> 09:23.400
She's living there
to avoid my censure.

09:23.400 --> 09:25.833
So no improvement
since your last letter?

09:25.833 --> 09:27.400
It's worse.

09:28.167 --> 09:29.800
I'm sorry.

09:29.800 --> 09:31.400
I know.
It's horrible.

09:32.067 --> 09:33.800
Can anyone talk to them?

09:33.800 --> 09:35.467
I've given up talking
to either of them.

09:35.467 --> 09:37.667
They're equally intransigent.

09:38.200 --> 09:40.267
Well, I'm not giving up on them.

09:40.267 --> 09:42.633
I've got my own plan.

09:42.633 --> 09:44.500
In my own time.

09:46.067 --> 09:48.500
[ Music continues ]

09:48.500 --> 09:50.533
[ Insects chirping ]

09:52.633 --> 09:54.667
[ Clock ticking ]

10:33.900 --> 10:36.600
[ Music continues ]

10:43.133 --> 10:45.333
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

11:06.733 --> 11:08.733
[ Laughs ]

11:08.733 --> 11:09.733
Oh.

11:09.733 --> 11:11.433
Oh!
[ Laughs ]

11:11.433 --> 11:15.967
* It almost breaks my heart
in two *

11:15.967 --> 11:17.667
[ Insects chirping ]

11:17.667 --> 11:20.200
I'm glad that we decided
to wait.

11:21.533 --> 11:24.200
To go back.

11:24.200 --> 11:26.700
Jack's in such pain.

11:26.700 --> 11:29.733
I can't leave
until I know that...

11:29.733 --> 11:34.533
that he's not so entrenched,
moving ahead somehow.

11:34.533 --> 11:36.967
You might want to get
your skates on.

11:37.867 --> 11:40.067
I wanted to surprise you.

11:41.200 --> 11:43.133
We met on a ship,

11:43.133 --> 11:46.933
so as we're about to embark on
the next phase in our lives...

11:50.800 --> 11:52.233
Good cabins are in demand,

11:52.233 --> 11:55.433
and most of the passages
already full.

11:55.433 --> 11:56.633
The Stratheden.

11:56.633 --> 11:58.067
Mm.

12:00.067 --> 12:01.900
Brand-new decade.

12:02.500 --> 12:03.900
Ours.

12:05.067 --> 12:06.633
George.

12:09.467 --> 12:13.067
So Christmas here,
then Hanukkah,

12:13.067 --> 12:15.733
New Year's, then...

12:15.733 --> 12:17.767
The 3rd of January.

12:18.800 --> 12:21.600
That's almost four months.

12:21.600 --> 12:24.667
If I can't make headway
with Jack by then...

12:26.333 --> 12:28.700
But I have to, don't I?

12:30.267 --> 12:33.367
[ Birds chirping ]

12:33.367 --> 12:36.100
You're back for your divorce,
Anna tells me.

12:36.100 --> 12:37.633
Finally.

12:37.633 --> 12:40.900
I go to court
the day after tomorrow.

12:40.900 --> 12:42.900
Can you keep it out
of the papers?

12:42.900 --> 12:45.433
Her solicitor says
there's a high-profile case

12:45.433 --> 12:48.267
on the same day, so they'll
ignore James and Livvy.

12:48.267 --> 12:49.700
Ah.

12:49.700 --> 12:51.867
Anyway.

12:51.867 --> 12:55.533
Uh...Andrew wanted to telephone,

12:55.533 --> 12:59.133
but...I wanted to tell you
in person.

13:00.567 --> 13:02.167
Andrew?

13:02.167 --> 13:03.967
My Andrew?

13:03.967 --> 13:05.967
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

13:05.967 --> 13:11.267
A couple of months ago, not long
after I arrived in France...

13:11.267 --> 13:15.467
Andrew was holidaying there,
and...we met up.

13:16.567 --> 13:18.767
On a yacht party, of all things.

13:18.767 --> 13:20.133
Sheer coincidence.

13:20.667 --> 13:24.167
[ Laughing ]
Oh, my goodness.

13:24.667 --> 13:26.500
Is that what you were
getting at?

13:26.500 --> 13:29.367
Oh, heavens.
I'm lost for words.

13:30.867 --> 13:33.367
I mean, I thought he'd turned
a new leaf when I saw him last,

13:33.367 --> 13:35.733
and his friends tell me so.

13:35.733 --> 13:39.733
But for you to -- and to...

13:39.733 --> 13:41.467
[ Gasps ]
Oh!

13:41.467 --> 13:44.067
Happy, happy mother!

13:44.067 --> 13:45.067
Oh!

13:45.067 --> 13:47.433
[ Laughs ]

13:50.333 --> 13:52.367
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

13:53.800 --> 13:55.767
PRUDENCE:
It's beautiful.

13:57.667 --> 13:59.133
Oh.
Are you sure, Livvy?

13:59.133 --> 14:01.067
Can we just take a breather
here?

14:01.067 --> 14:04.600
You, my dear,
will be the making of him.

14:04.600 --> 14:07.067
He's making himself, Prudence.

14:07.067 --> 14:09.800
He's doing very good work.

14:09.800 --> 14:14.067
And...James has given
his blessing.

14:14.600 --> 14:16.533
He really has transformed.

14:16.533 --> 14:19.067
Yes. Yes.
I hear he has --

14:19.067 --> 14:23.667
in that country
that starts with a "V."

14:23.667 --> 14:25.767
-[ Exhales sharply ]
-[ Chuckles ]

14:25.767 --> 14:27.900
Oh!
[ Laughs ]

14:28.467 --> 14:31.667
Vietnam.
He's probably a spy.

14:31.667 --> 14:33.400
He makes Livvy happy.

14:33.400 --> 14:35.200
Matt made Livvy happy.

14:35.200 --> 14:38.100
She's setting herself up
for another disaster.

14:38.833 --> 14:41.067
Mind you,
most relationships are that.

14:41.067 --> 14:42.567
Are what?

14:42.567 --> 14:44.567
Lives of quiet desperation.

14:44.567 --> 14:47.167
But then,
Andrew Swanson is a psychopath,

14:47.167 --> 14:49.233
so there'll never be
a dull moment, I'm sure.

14:49.233 --> 14:50.833
People change, Mama.

14:50.833 --> 14:54.433
Ah. People become more
of themselves.

14:54.433 --> 14:56.500
There isn't a shadow of doubt
on her face.

14:56.500 --> 14:58.067
He might be the one.

14:58.600 --> 15:02.267
There wasn't a shadow of doubt
on my face when I married Jack.

15:02.267 --> 15:06.867
And if you could just keep
that memory alive.

15:07.867 --> 15:10.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

15:11.833 --> 15:14.200
[ Children shouting ]

15:20.133 --> 15:21.833
Mum!

15:25.667 --> 15:27.333
Struth.

15:27.867 --> 15:30.400
[ Music continues ]

15:36.833 --> 15:38.067
Mrs. O'Rourke.

15:38.067 --> 15:40.100
He said someone might come by.

15:40.100 --> 15:41.600
I wasn't sure what he meant.

15:41.600 --> 15:43.600
We just got off the train.

15:43.600 --> 15:46.300
Ash Park's got
a food service going.

15:46.300 --> 15:47.833
Anyone in a bit of need.

15:48.400 --> 15:49.933
I see.

15:51.333 --> 15:53.767
Place is a terrible mess,
isn't it?

15:54.333 --> 15:56.967
You back for good
or you just visiting or...

15:56.967 --> 15:59.167
Well, he can't look after
himself.

16:00.500 --> 16:01.867
It's Mr. Briggs, Stan.

16:06.967 --> 16:10.533
One way to...
give the kids a f-fright.

16:13.800 --> 16:16.167
He said it's one way
to give the kids a fright.

16:17.800 --> 16:19.167
STAN:
Yeah.

16:21.800 --> 16:24.300
The yard needs work.
The whole place needs work.

16:24.300 --> 16:25.600
So I was thinking.

16:25.600 --> 16:27.600
You mentioned having trouble
getting blokes talking

16:27.600 --> 16:29.067
during these group things.

16:29.067 --> 16:30.600
But when men really get yarning

16:30.600 --> 16:33.933
is when they're building
something -- sawing, hammering.

16:33.933 --> 16:37.200
So maybe try setting up
a working bee type of thing,

16:37.200 --> 16:39.933
help people out who are
going through a rough patch.

16:39.933 --> 16:40.967
The O'Rourkes.

16:43.100 --> 16:45.067
Well, I need an icebreaker.

16:46.300 --> 16:48.067
This could be it.

16:49.833 --> 16:52.067
[ Clock ticking ]

16:52.067 --> 16:54.400
What's Andrew doing in Vietnam?

16:54.400 --> 16:56.067
Mama thinks he's a spy.

16:56.067 --> 16:58.167
[ Laughs ]

16:58.167 --> 17:02.067
He's working for the
International Rescue Committee,

17:02.067 --> 17:05.767
mostly in Europe
but Vietnam for the moment.

17:05.767 --> 17:08.233
He's resettling refugees,

17:08.233 --> 17:10.800
problems between north
and south.

17:10.800 --> 17:13.067
He's worried that a full-scale
war might break out there

17:13.067 --> 17:14.900
the way things are going.

17:14.900 --> 17:17.532
So he's kind to refugees.

17:18.166 --> 17:20.067
Is he kind to you?

17:20.867 --> 17:22.567
Don't be worried.

17:23.267 --> 17:26.599
I've seen the worst of Andrew.

17:26.599 --> 17:28.567
And now I've seen the best.

17:30.733 --> 17:33.067
He's a very different man.

17:33.933 --> 17:38.800
Well, now I know your secret,
I'll tell you mine.

17:40.167 --> 17:42.733
[ Hammer pounding in distance ]

17:42.733 --> 17:46.300
If you insist on going
to Inverness,

17:46.300 --> 17:50.700
which I think is a bad idea,
then you should leave today.

17:50.700 --> 17:53.867
Forget about my going to court.
I can go on my own, truly.

17:53.867 --> 17:55.967
I'm not taking no for an answer.

17:55.967 --> 17:57.800
It's why I've waited in town.

17:57.800 --> 18:00.700
This is a huge thing.
You will need support.

18:00.700 --> 18:02.067
Grandmother!

18:02.067 --> 18:04.567
Olivia's divorce day.
Tell her she can't go alone.

18:04.567 --> 18:06.833
-Oh, of course not.
-Thank you. I'm going with you.

18:06.833 --> 18:09.767
All I have to do
is go up on the stand,

18:09.767 --> 18:11.767
be questioned
by my own barrister --

18:11.767 --> 18:13.267
And I'll be there.

18:13.267 --> 18:15.967
I'll go to Inverness the next
day and wait to drop my bundle.

18:15.967 --> 18:18.567
Oh. So she's told you
about her silly notion.

18:18.567 --> 18:19.967
It's not a notion.

18:19.967 --> 18:21.767
Mama will have to go down
to see the baby.

18:21.767 --> 18:23.967
Papa will be there, and they
will break their impasse

18:23.967 --> 18:26.433
over the cradle and talk.

18:26.833 --> 18:28.867
Excuse me.
What's that?

18:31.267 --> 18:32.767
Oh.

18:33.767 --> 18:35.100
I have some news.

18:35.100 --> 18:37.767
-Some news.
-Well, tell me.

18:37.767 --> 18:39.600
Hold on to your hat.

18:39.600 --> 18:40.933
Anna!

18:40.933 --> 18:42.733
Nothing surprises me these days.

18:42.733 --> 18:44.133
Well, this will.

18:44.133 --> 18:47.233
A little bit of respect,
if you don't mind.

18:48.133 --> 18:50.233
Should I be sitting down?

18:50.767 --> 18:52.867
Well...

18:52.867 --> 18:54.933
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

18:54.933 --> 18:57.133
[ Birds chirping ]

18:57.133 --> 18:59.167
[ Rooster crows ]

19:00.467 --> 19:02.467
[ Children shouting ]

19:02.467 --> 19:06.233
JACK: There are some blokes
that meet up at the clinic

19:06.233 --> 19:08.733
for a cup of tea
and a natter sometimes.

19:08.733 --> 19:12.500
What they've said to me is...
tell us what needs fixing,

19:12.500 --> 19:15.067
what you need, and they'll do
their best to see it done.

19:15.567 --> 19:18.833
Well, we never replaced that
old chook house that blew over.

19:19.367 --> 19:20.867
Oh.
Well, good.

19:20.867 --> 19:23.700
Just decide where you want it
and we'll build you another one.

19:24.233 --> 19:27.100
Mowing.
Fences.

19:27.100 --> 19:29.300
Charity.

19:30.133 --> 19:31.767
It works both ways.

19:31.767 --> 19:34.200
[ Vehicle approaching ]

19:38.200 --> 19:39.367
[ Door opens ]

19:39.367 --> 19:40.833
We'll set up a day that suits.

19:40.833 --> 19:42.667
Thank you, Dr. Duncan.

19:42.667 --> 19:44.133
Mrs. O'Rourke, Stan.

19:44.133 --> 19:46.233
[ Door closes ]

19:50.500 --> 19:52.667
Sorry to intrude.

19:52.667 --> 19:55.767
Trying to persuade him
to let the men's group help out.

19:55.767 --> 19:57.900
Roy said that Sheila was back,

19:57.900 --> 20:00.933
and it's about time
I had a word to Stan, so...

20:01.500 --> 20:03.367
I'll wait for you.

20:04.133 --> 20:06.100
I won't be long.

20:09.233 --> 20:11.967
It's lovely to see you,
Mrs. Bligh.

20:11.967 --> 20:13.967
And you, Sheila.

20:13.967 --> 20:15.667
How are you?

20:16.700 --> 20:19.633
Healthwise I'm really good,
but...

20:24.167 --> 20:25.867
Of course.

20:33.000 --> 20:35.033
Mr. O'Rourke.

20:38.067 --> 20:39.267
What?

20:40.833 --> 20:45.400
I, uh...I've been thinking.

20:46.467 --> 20:48.633
I wanted to let you know that...

20:49.567 --> 20:53.333
...that there's no hostility
on my part.

20:53.333 --> 20:56.200
No hard feelings, not anymore.

20:59.533 --> 21:01.233
All right.

21:01.233 --> 21:02.933
You said your bit.

21:04.067 --> 21:05.500
Now piss off.

21:05.500 --> 21:06.667
He said that he --

21:06.667 --> 21:08.733
Thank you, Sheila.

21:08.733 --> 21:09.933
I understood.

21:15.167 --> 21:16.833
Whatever Jack's offered
with the men,

21:16.833 --> 21:19.067
just know it comes
in good faith.

21:21.667 --> 21:23.733
And in any way we can help.

21:27.067 --> 21:28.633
Thank you.

21:35.300 --> 21:37.533
You know you didn't mean that.

21:38.067 --> 21:41.200
An apology would have meant
the world to her.

21:41.200 --> 21:42.900
Would it have hurt you?

21:42.900 --> 21:45.867
Everyone is trying to help.

21:46.667 --> 21:49.200
[ Children shouting ]

21:51.500 --> 21:53.767
That was a mistake and a half.

21:53.767 --> 21:55.600
He's his own worst enemy.

21:55.600 --> 21:57.400
Stubborn as a mule.

21:58.733 --> 21:59.567
What?

22:00.700 --> 22:02.800
Well, it's interesting
you say that.

22:02.800 --> 22:03.800
Here we go.

22:03.800 --> 22:06.200
I remember
someone asking me once

22:06.200 --> 22:08.800
would I rather be right
or be happy?

22:08.800 --> 22:10.633
It forced me to swallow
my pride.

22:10.633 --> 22:12.967
Jesus wept.
Will you give it a break?

22:13.867 --> 22:15.867
I don't need to talk to her.

22:15.867 --> 22:17.867
She's gone.

22:17.867 --> 22:20.567
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

22:22.267 --> 22:23.800
[ Engine starts ]

22:28.267 --> 22:30.367
[ Insects chirping ]

22:31.367 --> 22:33.833
I could have strangled him.

22:33.833 --> 22:36.100
He's with all these men
he's supposed to be counseling,

22:36.100 --> 22:38.067
but physician heal thyself?

22:38.067 --> 22:40.700
-Forget it.
-He's feeling sorry for himself.

22:40.700 --> 22:43.167
No, he's drowning in self-pity.

22:43.167 --> 22:45.467
From Stan,
I could almost take it.

22:45.467 --> 22:48.333
Yes.
Well, his future is rather grim.

22:50.733 --> 22:52.833
I should put Jack
in the same room as Leah.

22:53.400 --> 22:54.500
All those years --

22:54.500 --> 22:57.133
years as a child,
confined to bed.

22:57.133 --> 22:59.467
If anyone had the right
to wallow, but no.

22:59.467 --> 23:02.300
She heads off to a new country,
mapping out a new life.

23:02.300 --> 23:07.433
To be fair...when I lost you,
I went off the rails.

23:08.500 --> 23:10.733
With rather disastrous
consequences.

23:13.933 --> 23:16.533
One more try with Jack.

23:16.533 --> 23:18.133
And then...

23:19.400 --> 23:21.100
Then I give up.

23:22.500 --> 23:24.833
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

23:24.833 --> 23:26.967
[ Birds chirping ]

23:26.967 --> 23:29.067
[ Vehicle approaching ]

23:35.067 --> 23:38.100
[ Cows lowing ]

23:41.067 --> 23:43.067
[ Engine shuts off ]

23:56.667 --> 23:58.667
This is a surprise.

23:58.667 --> 24:00.767
I wanted to let you know
they've offered me a position

24:00.767 --> 24:02.233
at the hospital.

24:02.833 --> 24:05.733
Assisting Mr. Rowe,
the new surgeon,

24:05.733 --> 24:07.767
in whatever capacity
I can manage.

24:09.900 --> 24:11.267
Well, good.

24:12.300 --> 24:15.833
But you should know
that I'm going to turn it down.

24:16.867 --> 24:18.100
Uh, because of us.

24:20.667 --> 24:22.067
Sure.

24:25.767 --> 24:27.767
Because in my eyes,

24:27.767 --> 24:30.400
and unless you've changed
your mind...

24:32.800 --> 24:34.500
...I'd like us to be together.

24:36.400 --> 24:37.433
More.

24:39.100 --> 24:40.600
How's that?

24:42.700 --> 24:44.967
Well, with James and I,
it was different.

24:46.067 --> 24:48.900
We were living in the same house
without suspicion.

24:49.633 --> 24:50.800
But if I were working here,

24:50.800 --> 24:53.833
living in the surgeon's
quarters...

24:54.400 --> 24:56.300
...we'd spend half our time
sneaking around,

24:56.300 --> 24:58.967
and it'd be living a lie.

24:58.967 --> 25:01.400
It'd be Doris all over again.

25:01.400 --> 25:02.600
Or worse.

25:04.533 --> 25:07.233
But if you're up
in the big smoke...

25:07.233 --> 25:08.633
You could come up.

25:10.800 --> 25:13.067
And occasionally...

25:14.167 --> 25:16.367
...this would be my weekender.

25:18.600 --> 25:21.867
No one would know that I'm here.

25:21.867 --> 25:24.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

25:24.067 --> 25:25.833
Not to be away from you, to...

25:27.633 --> 25:29.667
...to be with you, yeah?

25:34.867 --> 25:36.067
See how it goes.

25:40.733 --> 25:42.400
See how it goes.

25:51.267 --> 25:54.100
[ Music continues ]

25:54.100 --> 25:56.800
[ Door closes, engine starts ]

25:58.933 --> 26:01.567
[ Horn blows ]

26:03.233 --> 26:06.267
[ Indistinct conversations,
telephone ringing ]

26:18.733 --> 26:19.933
It's over.

26:21.100 --> 26:23.900
I don't know why,
but I feel rather brokenhearted.

26:23.900 --> 26:25.767
Oh.

26:26.433 --> 26:28.367
-Are you all right?
-Me?

26:28.367 --> 26:30.800
You're wearing
a strange expression.

26:31.500 --> 26:33.533
Just indigestion.

26:36.133 --> 26:40.067
Anna, you asked me before
what a contraction feels like.

26:40.067 --> 26:41.633
I just have to make
a quick call.

26:41.633 --> 26:42.900
Anna.

26:43.367 --> 26:44.700
-Anna.
-Well, I've only had two.

26:44.700 --> 26:46.733
I've got plenty of time.

26:46.733 --> 26:48.667
Ooh.
[ Exhales deeply ]

26:48.667 --> 26:50.600
Oh.

26:50.600 --> 26:52.567
Three.

26:52.567 --> 26:55.067
-[ Moans ]
-All -- All right.

26:55.067 --> 26:56.333
Um...

26:56.333 --> 26:59.567
Um...
[ Exhales deeply ]

27:00.500 --> 27:02.800
ANNA:
Grandmother, don't panic.

27:02.800 --> 27:04.967
All I need is a car and a driver

27:04.967 --> 27:07.400
and for you to gather
some things from my room.

27:07.400 --> 27:11.300
If you have started your labor,
you absolutely cannot travel.

27:11.300 --> 27:13.367
Grandmother, please just arrange
for a car to be there

27:13.367 --> 27:14.500
when we arrive.

27:14.500 --> 27:16.333
A car to take you
to hospital here,

27:16.333 --> 27:17.633
not all the way down there.

27:17.633 --> 27:20.067
I am getting myself
to Inverness

27:20.067 --> 27:21.900
with your help or without.

27:21.900 --> 27:24.700
Anna, this is
a ridiculous notion.

27:24.700 --> 27:25.967
It is absurd.

27:25.967 --> 27:27.900
Did Dawn Briggs
teach you nothing?

27:27.900 --> 27:29.267
It's how I want it to be.

27:29.267 --> 27:31.133
And please telephone Mama
and let her know.

27:31.133 --> 27:32.533
I won't be part of this.

27:32.533 --> 27:36.400
Grandmother, I thought I had
more time, and now I don't!

27:36.400 --> 27:37.833
I will see you shortly.

27:37.833 --> 27:40.200
[ Click, dial tone ]

27:42.867 --> 27:45.233
[ Up-tempo music plays ]

27:54.333 --> 27:56.300
[ Engine revs ]

27:58.333 --> 28:00.567
[ Music continues ]

28:00.567 --> 28:02.933
[ Telephone ringing ]

28:05.767 --> 28:08.067
Sorry for interrupting, Mr. --

28:08.067 --> 28:09.067
Oh. Henry.

28:09.567 --> 28:12.067
Oh, good.
Uh, just the person I need.

28:12.067 --> 28:13.200
Would you excuse us?

28:13.200 --> 28:15.167
We were just finishing up.

28:15.167 --> 28:17.467
Uh, next time you're in
the city, let's have that drink.

28:17.467 --> 28:18.533
I look forward to it.

28:20.600 --> 28:22.233
Come on, Dad.

28:22.233 --> 28:24.300
Your timing's perfect.

28:24.933 --> 28:27.367
ANNA:
[ Groaning ]

28:31.400 --> 28:33.667
Do you always drive
like a snail?

28:34.333 --> 28:35.800
No, Elizabeth.

28:35.800 --> 28:37.633
ELIZABETH:
It was a rhetorical question.

28:37.633 --> 28:39.767
But we could walk there
faster than this.

28:39.767 --> 28:42.067
Don't tell me you motor
at this pace on the Riviera.

28:42.067 --> 28:43.667
As a matter of fact...

28:43.667 --> 28:45.767
-[ Engine revs ]
-[ Gasps ]

28:47.233 --> 28:49.100
...I don't.

28:49.100 --> 28:51.900
[ Sighs ]
You definitely spoke with Mama?

28:51.900 --> 28:54.500
-Yes. Yes, I did, darling.
-Okay. Thank you.

28:55.800 --> 28:58.100
[ Groans ]

28:58.667 --> 29:01.333
This is typical Anna.

29:01.333 --> 29:03.067
I know why she's doing this --

29:03.067 --> 29:06.067
so that I'll charge down
to Inverness Hospital

29:06.067 --> 29:10.667
and have no choice but to sit
in the corridor with Jack.

29:11.433 --> 29:13.867
I could take you if you like.

29:13.867 --> 29:15.167
[ Sighs ]

29:15.167 --> 29:17.533
That's not going to help anyone.

29:18.700 --> 29:20.933
I'll go when it's time.

29:22.067 --> 29:23.600
But thank you.

29:25.300 --> 29:28.967
And...thank you.

29:32.167 --> 29:34.167
[ Up-tempo music plays ]

29:34.167 --> 29:38.133
ELIZABETH: You know, I-I thought
you would have matured by now.

29:38.133 --> 29:40.367
You're like a bull
in a china shop.

29:40.367 --> 29:41.533
You want it all your way.

29:41.533 --> 29:42.800
Right back to Gino --

29:42.800 --> 29:45.233
too stubborn to see
how inappropriate that was.

29:45.233 --> 29:47.067
I thought you'd stopped
being critical!

29:47.067 --> 29:48.733
I'm doing my best.

29:48.733 --> 29:49.767
[ Moans ]

29:49.767 --> 29:51.733
-Slow down.
-I can't! [ Sobs ]

29:51.733 --> 29:52.933
No, darling.
Not you.

29:52.933 --> 29:54.967
Olivia, one minute
you're Terry Tortoise,

29:54.967 --> 29:57.100
the next minute
you're Jack Brabham.

29:57.100 --> 29:59.600
I'm sorry, Elizabeth,
and this isn't easy to say --

29:59.600 --> 30:01.200
Don't hold back.
No one else is.

30:01.200 --> 30:05.300
Will you please shut up
and let me drive?!

30:06.500 --> 30:08.000
[ Laughs ]

30:08.000 --> 30:09.633
Mock me all you like.

30:10.567 --> 30:13.000
I shall just be happy
if we arrive in one piece.

30:16.333 --> 30:19.033
SARAH: Knowing I'd meet with
them gave Elizabeth reassurance.

30:19.600 --> 30:21.500
Are you with me?

30:21.500 --> 30:23.300
Uh, yeah.
Yes.

30:23.300 --> 30:26.467
[ Music continues ]

30:27.267 --> 30:30.467
ELIZABETH: One minute long
and three minutes apart?

30:30.467 --> 30:32.200
-[ Moans ]
-That can't be right. Um...

30:32.200 --> 30:33.867
Stop the car.
Stop the car!

30:33.867 --> 30:36.567
If you can just hold on,
we're not too far away.

30:36.567 --> 30:38.400
Now, Livvy! Now!
I need to get out!

30:38.400 --> 30:39.233
Stop!

30:39.233 --> 30:40.533
-Stop!
-Stop!

30:40.533 --> 30:41.700
I am!

30:41.700 --> 30:43.300
ELIZABETH:
Wait! Just hold on, darling.

30:43.300 --> 30:45.733
Hold on, hold on, hold on.
No, no, no.

30:52.433 --> 30:54.567
Do you think they've come
a different way?

30:54.567 --> 30:56.567
No.
We'll find them.

30:57.733 --> 31:01.333
All fathers get nervous.
It's part of the package.

31:01.333 --> 31:03.967
It's just that I know
what can go wrong.

31:06.367 --> 31:08.900
[ Moaning ]

31:11.167 --> 31:12.667
Oh, Olivia, I'm so hot!

31:12.667 --> 31:14.100
Here.
Here.

31:14.100 --> 31:15.567
[ Breathing heavily ]

31:15.567 --> 31:18.567
[ Groans ]

31:18.567 --> 31:20.200
I'm no expert, Anna,

31:20.200 --> 31:22.567
but I don't think you should try
and push just yet, darling.

31:23.767 --> 31:25.100
I need....

31:25.100 --> 31:27.567
Oh, I need --
I need an ambulance!

31:27.567 --> 31:30.433
I think we'll all need
an ambulance before too long.

31:31.600 --> 31:33.833
W-What if they just drive past?

31:34.367 --> 31:36.267
Perhaps I should run to the road
and check.

31:36.267 --> 31:37.933
Yes.
Yes, you do that.

31:37.933 --> 31:39.600
I'll stay with Anna.

31:39.600 --> 31:41.667
Oh, it's all right, sweetheart.
It's all right.

31:41.667 --> 31:43.500
-It's all right.
-I'm here. I'm here.

31:43.500 --> 31:45.467
Grandma's here.
It's all right, darling.

31:45.467 --> 31:47.967
You're doing so well, darling.
Just try.

31:47.967 --> 31:49.500
-Try really hard.
-[ Groans ]

31:49.500 --> 31:52.067
Try really hard to just...

31:52.067 --> 31:54.600
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

32:08.833 --> 32:10.467
Oh, thank God.

32:10.467 --> 32:12.467
[ Brake clicks,
engine shuts off ]

32:12.467 --> 32:16.067
She's just down here.
Quickly!

32:17.333 --> 32:19.100
Oh, thank the Lord!

32:19.100 --> 32:20.900
-Here they come. They're coming.
-They're coming!

32:20.900 --> 32:23.800
ELIZABETH: You'll be all right.
You'll be all right. Hold on.

32:23.800 --> 32:26.067
[ Music continues ]

32:27.933 --> 32:31.267
This time tomorrow,
you'll be a grandmother.

32:31.267 --> 32:33.500
[ Clock ticking ]

32:33.500 --> 32:35.367
Yes.

32:38.233 --> 32:40.667
You want to be there, don't you?

32:43.367 --> 32:44.867
Yes.

32:49.967 --> 32:52.733
[ Music continues ]

32:52.733 --> 32:54.667
ANNA:
[ Moaning ]

32:54.667 --> 32:56.867
Ah.
My hand.

32:56.867 --> 32:58.667
SARAH:
And -- And push now!

32:58.667 --> 33:01.100
[ Groaning ]

33:01.100 --> 33:02.467
Okay.
Stop.

33:02.933 --> 33:03.800
Stop.

33:03.800 --> 33:06.067
-Stop.
-Shut up! I heard!

33:06.067 --> 33:07.567
[ Groaning ]

33:07.567 --> 33:09.667
That's it.
Let it go.

33:09.667 --> 33:11.500
Let it --
Okay.

33:11.500 --> 33:13.767
-ANNA: [ Sobs ]
-OLIVIA: You can do this.

33:13.767 --> 33:17.467
[ Groans, sobs ]

33:20.500 --> 33:22.300
And another one if you can.

33:22.300 --> 33:24.833
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

33:26.100 --> 33:29.333
That's it!
Keep pushing!

33:35.567 --> 33:37.233
[ Baby crying ]

33:37.233 --> 33:39.967
[ Music continues ]

33:39.967 --> 33:42.667
ANNA:
[ Sobs ]

33:42.667 --> 33:44.400
Well done.
Another Miss Bligh!

33:44.400 --> 33:47.233
[ Music continues ]

33:47.233 --> 33:48.933
Oh!
Oh!

34:06.167 --> 34:08.333
[ Insects chirping ]

34:14.433 --> 34:16.567
She's perfect.

34:16.567 --> 34:19.733
I can't remember a time
when she wasn't here.

34:22.766 --> 34:23.833
[ Tapping ]

34:42.567 --> 34:44.800
I shouldn't have come.

34:44.800 --> 34:46.132
Jack?

34:46.199 --> 34:47.667
Jack!

34:47.667 --> 34:51.699
Your daughter risked her life
and the baby's life for this.

34:51.699 --> 34:53.533
Well, more fool her.

34:53.533 --> 34:55.533
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

34:55.533 --> 34:57.567
[ Sighs ]

35:00.933 --> 35:03.433
[ Footsteps approaching ]

35:08.933 --> 35:13.067
Oh.
What a lucky little girl she is.

35:14.767 --> 35:15.967
Miss Bligh.

35:17.900 --> 35:19.700
Uncle Harry.

35:19.700 --> 35:22.067
[ Music continues ]

35:27.833 --> 35:30.533
Four generations.
[ Chuckles ]

35:31.533 --> 35:33.233
Four.

35:35.067 --> 35:37.067
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

35:46.833 --> 35:49.367
[ Baby cooing ]

35:54.667 --> 35:56.400
You're here early.

35:59.567 --> 36:01.800
Hello, little one.

36:02.333 --> 36:03.567
"Dot and the Kangaroo."

36:03.567 --> 36:05.567
Oh!
This is my favorite!

36:05.567 --> 36:07.433
She'll love it.

36:08.733 --> 36:12.400
I've decided to let Caro
have the day.

36:12.933 --> 36:14.433
No, Papa.

36:14.433 --> 36:15.500
Please stay.

36:15.500 --> 36:16.800
[ Clears throat ]

36:16.800 --> 36:20.333
Like Roy with Dawn's funeral,
best not get in the way.

36:21.067 --> 36:22.900
But you won't be.

36:22.900 --> 36:24.267
[ Voice breaking ]
Please.

36:25.067 --> 36:26.767
You all enjoy yourselves.

36:27.467 --> 36:29.067
No.

36:30.067 --> 36:32.067
You're a beautiful mother.

36:33.733 --> 36:35.767
Or have I said that before?

36:37.367 --> 36:39.567
I'll be here in spirit.

36:48.067 --> 36:50.167
It's all rather intriguing,
isn't it?

36:50.167 --> 36:51.867
A naming ceremony.

36:51.867 --> 36:53.133
What do you think it means?

36:53.133 --> 36:54.733
Well, sort of like
a christening,

36:54.733 --> 36:57.233
but we're not in a church, so...

36:57.233 --> 37:00.667
Well, of course Miss Anna
was C of E,

37:00.667 --> 37:04.600
then Roman Catholic,
so perhaps to avoid confusion.

37:04.600 --> 37:07.967
You know, I did read once
about naming ceremonies

37:07.967 --> 37:09.633
in the National Geographic.

37:09.633 --> 37:14.333
Somewhere in Africa or...India
or somewhere.

37:14.333 --> 37:16.900
Well, then there's the father
and his chappie.

37:16.900 --> 37:17.933
Oh.

37:17.933 --> 37:20.567
Do you know,
I did ask Mr. Polson

37:20.567 --> 37:22.567
what his sort likes
to be called.

37:22.567 --> 37:24.900
-Struth, Doris!
-Do you know what he said?

37:24.900 --> 37:26.733
"Just not late for dinner."

37:26.733 --> 37:28.567
[ Both laugh ]

37:28.567 --> 37:32.433
We're in the thick of bohemia
now, Mr. Briggs.

37:32.433 --> 37:34.233
The modern age.

37:34.233 --> 37:36.833
All we need is the Sputnik
to fly past the window.

37:36.833 --> 37:38.500
[ Chuckles ]

37:38.500 --> 37:41.067
[ Indistinct conversations ]

37:49.867 --> 37:52.267
Papa decided not to come.

37:54.133 --> 37:56.133
Not today, darling.

37:56.133 --> 37:58.567
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

38:01.467 --> 38:03.933
DELIA: I thought
you'd probably be there.

38:03.933 --> 38:05.433
If you were up
at the christening,

38:05.433 --> 38:07.067
I wouldn't need to say this.

38:07.067 --> 38:09.733
But as you're hidden away, I do.

38:10.267 --> 38:12.600
Say what?
Why are you calling me?

38:12.600 --> 38:16.167
Because I'm sick of seeing
Carolyn so unhappy.

38:16.167 --> 38:17.667
This is our business, not yours.

38:17.667 --> 38:20.100
It most certainly is
my business,

38:20.100 --> 38:24.267
until you find the gumption to
talk with her at the very least.

38:24.267 --> 38:25.400
I'm hanging up.

38:25.400 --> 38:28.467
I can only respect your marriage
for so long.

38:28.467 --> 38:32.067
If you want her back,
get on with it.

38:32.067 --> 38:36.300
But if you don't fight for her,
I will take her from you.

38:36.300 --> 38:37.767
She's not a chess piece.

38:37.767 --> 38:41.200
No, she isn't.
She's a magnificent woman.

38:41.200 --> 38:44.133
And if I get her, it'll be
because you were too vindictive,

38:44.133 --> 38:48.100
too focused on your own needs
and you let her slip away.

38:49.600 --> 38:51.633
[ Click, dial tone ]

38:56.133 --> 38:58.500
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

39:07.533 --> 39:09.133
Here we all are.

39:09.133 --> 39:11.067
Thank you for coming.

39:11.067 --> 39:14.267
James, you get the prize
for longest distance.

39:14.967 --> 39:19.300
I first learned about
naming ceremonies in Hawaii,

39:19.300 --> 39:20.900
from a Japanese community.

39:20.900 --> 39:23.067
Hawaii! Of course.
That was it.

39:23.067 --> 39:26.667
So this is "The Prophet"
by Kahlil Gibran.

39:26.667 --> 39:28.533
He's a poet from Lebanon,

39:28.533 --> 39:31.733
and he was first published
over 30 years ago.

39:31.733 --> 39:33.800
"On Children."

39:35.467 --> 39:39.867
"Your children are not
your children.

39:39.867 --> 39:44.133
They are the sons and daughters
of life's longing for itself."

39:46.900 --> 39:51.400
"They come through you
but not from you.

39:51.400 --> 39:56.133
And though they are with you,
yet they belong not to you,

39:56.133 --> 40:00.533
you may give them your love
but not your thoughts...

40:01.467 --> 40:03.667
...for they have
their own thoughts."

40:06.167 --> 40:10.133
Um..."You may house their bodies
but not their souls,

40:10.133 --> 40:13.233
for their souls dwell
in the house of tomorrow,

40:13.233 --> 40:17.133
which you cannot visit,
not even in your dreams."

40:19.833 --> 40:23.800
"You may strive to be like them,

40:23.800 --> 40:25.800
but seek not to make them
like you...

40:27.533 --> 40:33.067
...for life goes not backward
or tarries with yesterday."

40:35.533 --> 40:36.800
"You are the bows

40:36.800 --> 40:40.200
from which your children
as living arrows are sent forth.

40:41.367 --> 40:45.300
The archer sees the mark
upon the path of the infinite,

40:45.300 --> 40:48.500
and he bends you with his might

40:48.500 --> 40:53.167
that his arrows may go swift
and far."

40:56.500 --> 41:02.533
"Let your bending in the
archer's hand be for gladness,

41:02.533 --> 41:06.233
for even as he loves the arrow
that flies,

41:06.233 --> 41:10.167
so he loves also the bow
that is stable."

41:10.833 --> 41:12.100
"On Children."

41:14.733 --> 41:16.433
Thank you.

41:17.067 --> 41:23.133
In the presence of you all,
family and dear friends

41:23.133 --> 41:30.233
and a wonderful father,
we name this child Elaine.

41:32.067 --> 41:34.933
Elaine Elizabeth Bligh.

41:34.933 --> 41:36.133
Oh.

41:36.133 --> 41:38.100
Oh, thank you.

41:39.233 --> 41:41.067
Thank you.

41:41.867 --> 41:44.533
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

41:44.533 --> 41:46.967
[ Applause ]

41:57.767 --> 41:58.900
What are you guys doing?

41:58.900 --> 42:05.333
"Your children...
are not your children.

42:05.333 --> 42:07.833
Children.
They are..."

42:07.833 --> 42:09.500
I'll be heading off in a minute.

42:09.500 --> 42:11.400
I have work to do.

42:11.400 --> 42:13.833
Now, Carolyn,
you're doing a wonderful job,

42:13.833 --> 42:15.667
but under the circumstances,

42:15.667 --> 42:17.833
if working with Delia
is too problematic --

42:17.833 --> 42:19.533
It's not.
Not at all.

42:19.533 --> 42:22.467
I bear a burden of the guilt.
I set the thing in motion.

42:23.067 --> 42:24.967
No hard feelings
if you want to take a step away.

42:24.967 --> 42:26.067
That's all.

42:26.067 --> 42:27.900
It needed to be this way.

42:27.900 --> 42:29.100
I'll be fine.

42:29.100 --> 42:31.133
Oh.
[ Exhales deeply ]

42:32.233 --> 42:34.133
Safe travels.

42:40.133 --> 42:42.500
Congratulations again.

42:44.500 --> 42:46.267
And you two.

42:49.533 --> 42:50.767
I'm glad.

42:51.333 --> 42:52.500
Cheers.

42:52.500 --> 42:54.333
I'm grateful to your family
for including me.

42:54.333 --> 42:55.567
Not everyone would.

42:55.567 --> 42:57.533
I'd have burnt the house down
if they hadn't.

42:57.533 --> 42:59.600
So would I.

43:02.233 --> 43:03.400
Father.

43:03.400 --> 43:05.233
Son.

43:05.233 --> 43:07.600
It's just about the New Year.

43:07.600 --> 43:11.633
I hope you don't mind, but I was
going to head back to France.

43:11.633 --> 43:14.700
Just seeing in the '60s
and, uh...

43:14.700 --> 43:16.200
I see.
I see.

43:16.200 --> 43:21.133
Um...New Year's Eve here
or on the Riviera.

43:22.067 --> 43:23.733
Yes.

43:23.733 --> 43:26.933
Well, it's hardly a choice,
is it, George?

43:26.933 --> 43:28.733
It certainly is not.

43:31.067 --> 43:32.433
Be mad if you didn't.

43:32.433 --> 43:35.100
[ Chuckles ]

43:35.100 --> 43:36.600
Thank you.

43:36.600 --> 43:38.667
We'll meet up with you
over there soon.

43:38.667 --> 43:41.933
It is literally next year
in Jerusalem.

43:45.500 --> 43:47.067
[ Insects chirping ]

43:47.067 --> 43:48.667
Did Jack come?

43:48.667 --> 43:50.233
No.

43:50.700 --> 43:52.900
He doesn't deserve you.

43:52.900 --> 43:54.967
Not the way he is.

43:54.967 --> 43:57.333
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

44:01.800 --> 44:04.333
[ Dog barking in distance ]

44:05.233 --> 44:08.400
[ Cooing ]

44:12.433 --> 44:15.067
She was very good today.

44:15.067 --> 44:17.067
Elaine Elizabeth.

44:21.333 --> 44:25.200
This is the last thing I'll say,
and then I give up.

44:26.333 --> 44:27.467
Good.

44:27.967 --> 44:30.967
Why do you think it's so hard
to move ahead?

44:31.600 --> 44:33.767
To fit yourself in
to what Carolyn wants?

44:33.767 --> 44:35.433
Oh.

44:36.467 --> 44:38.167
Why should I?

44:39.400 --> 44:42.167
I've got the hospital.
I've got the clinic growing.

44:42.167 --> 44:44.167
And you'll most likely
be doing it all alone.

44:44.167 --> 44:45.200
So be it.

44:45.933 --> 44:47.667
Really?

44:49.533 --> 44:51.900
You know what I can't forgive?

44:53.300 --> 44:56.267
I stood in that doorway,
and I saw what I saw.

44:56.267 --> 44:58.067
Bad enough the Japs
cut my balls off.

44:58.067 --> 45:00.200
The woman I love
just did it all over again,

45:00.200 --> 45:03.067
everything rationalized
by her standard old accusation

45:03.067 --> 45:04.067
that I am in a rut.

45:04.067 --> 45:05.200
I think you are.

45:05.200 --> 45:07.767
-Enough, all right?
-We both have been.

45:07.767 --> 45:11.067
You know, you and I, we are
opposite sides of the same coin.

45:11.567 --> 45:13.900
Because of my war damage,
I ran and couldn't stop.

45:13.900 --> 45:16.333
Because of your war damage,
you can't move.

45:16.333 --> 45:17.767
-That's not right.
-Listen.

45:17.767 --> 45:22.400
We were both brutalized every
hour of every day for years,

45:22.400 --> 45:25.267
until we almost forgot
who we were.

45:26.100 --> 45:28.600
What would anyone do
who went through what we did?

45:28.600 --> 45:30.867
You -- You --
You find what feels safe

45:30.867 --> 45:32.167
and you hold on tight.

45:33.333 --> 45:36.533
It was safer for me to run
from happiness than embrace it.

45:36.533 --> 45:40.067
It's safer for you to be here
alone than risk change.

45:40.067 --> 45:42.233
These things,
they become habits.

45:42.767 --> 45:45.333
And we're too scared
to shake them off.

45:48.500 --> 45:51.767
You know, perhaps we will always
be revisited by our terrors.

45:53.767 --> 45:56.867
But it's another thing
to keep creating them.

45:58.233 --> 45:59.600
Hmm?

46:01.900 --> 46:05.967
I think you have to do
something big, Jack,

46:05.967 --> 46:08.233
or you won't be any good
to anyone,

46:08.233 --> 46:10.533
including this little girl.

46:10.533 --> 46:12.233
[ Cooing ]

46:12.233 --> 46:15.167
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

